{
  "$schema": "https://aka.ms/codetour-schema",
  "title": "15 — Sovereign Export & Encryption",
  "description": "This tour walks `internal/export`: how Balaur writes a one-way Markdown mirror of the owner's knowledge into a Johnny Decimal folder tree, commits it to a local git history, optionally encrypts it with scrypt + AES-256-GCM, and enforces the redaction boundary that makes it safe to carry off-box. It covers the JD type map, the mirror writer, the deterministic renderer, the encryption envelope, and the canary test that proves no secret ever reaches the mirror.",
  "steps": [
    {
      "file": "internal/export/export.go",
      "line": 61,
      "title": "15.1 — The Johnny Decimal type map",
      "description": "```go\nvar jdFolder = map[string]string{\n    \"note\":   \"10-19 Knowledge/11 Notes\",\n    \"idea\":   \"10-19 Knowledge/12 Ideas\",\n    \"person\": \"20-29 People/21 People\",\n    \"book\":   \"30-39 Library/31 Books\",\n    \"place\":  \"40-49 Places/41 Places\",\n}\n```\n\n`jdFolder` is the single mapping from node type to its Johnny Decimal folder path — a deliberate, human-readable structure (`10-19 Knowledge/11 Notes`) that survives a full re-export unchanged. Any type not present in the map falls back to the `unsortedFolder` bucket (`90-99 Unsorted/91 Other`) via `jdFolderFor`.\n\nNotice that `day` and `task` are absent — they belong in the JD design (`50-59 Journal`, `60-69 Tasks`) but are listed in `deferredTypes` instead. Their recap and task content needs its own redaction pass before it is safe to export. **Do not add a type here without simultaneously removing it from `deferredTypes` and landing a leak test.**\n\nThis is one concrete expression of YAGNI / KISS: ship the safe subset, gate the rest behind an explicit defer list rather than a flag or config knob."
    },
    {
      "file": "internal/export/export.go",
      "line": 114,
      "title": "15.2 — The mirror writer",
      "description": "```go\nfunc ExportMirror(app core.App, destDir string) ([]string, error)\n```\n\n`ExportMirror` is the top-level entry point for the one-way Markdown mirror. It:\n\n1. Calls `nodes.OwnerAuthoredTypes` to discover which types exist — no hard-coded list.\n2. Sorts the type list so iteration order is deterministic.\n3. Skips `deferredTypes` (`day`, `task`) entirely — they are never opened, never read, never written.\n4. For each remaining type, calls `nodes.ListByTypeStatus(app, typ, nodes.StatusActive)` — the consent filter that restricts the read to `active` rows only.\n5. Routes each type to its JD folder via `jdFolderFor` and writes one `.md` file per record.\n6. After writing, calls `commitMirror(destDir)` to commit the state to a local git history under the export directory. Between writing and committing, pruneStale removes any stale .md file from the managed JD folders (archived/dropped/renamed nodes), so the working tree always holds exactly one file per ACTIVE node and git add -A records the deletions.\n\nThe function is **read-only on PocketBase**: it never opens `llm_providers`, `llm_models`, `extensions`, `owner_settings`, `audit_log`, or any token/secret collection. The canary test in step 15.6 asserts this invariant at the collection level.\n\nThe return value is the sorted list of relative slash-separated paths written — deterministic so a second run on unchanged data returns the same list.\n\nAGENTS.md invariant: *keep context transparent — durable state lives in PocketBase collections, inspectable SQLite, and exported Markdown.* The mirror is that exported Markdown layer.\n\nSee **Tour 14** for the `nodes` package and the unified object spine."
    },
    {
      "file": "internal/export/export.go",
      "line": 235,
      "title": "15.3 — Deterministic rendering",
      "description": "```go\nfunc render(rec *core.Record) []byte\n```\n\n`render` builds the Markdown for one node: YAML frontmatter followed by an H1 title and the node body verbatim.\n\nThree design decisions keep the output deterministic (identical bytes on a second run over unchanged data):\n\n1. **Frontmatter field order is fixed**: `type`, `status`, `created`, `updated` appear first, always in that sequence.\n2. **Props keys are sorted**: `slices.Sort(keys)` before the loop so the same props always produce the same frontmatter lines, regardless of Go map iteration order.\n3. **No `time.Now()` calls**: timestamps come from the record's own `created`/`updated` fields. A second export at a different wall-clock time is byte-identical for unchanged data.\n\nDeterminism matters because the mirror is committed to git — an export that produces trivial diffs for unchanged data would pollute the git history with noise commits. The `git diff --cached --quiet` check in `commitMirror` can correctly detect a clean tree only because render is stable.\n\nValues are `%q`-quoted via `yamlLine` so a colon, quote, or newline in a title or prop value cannot break the YAML structure."
    },
    {
      "file": "internal/export/export.go",
      "line": 1,
      "title": "15.4 — The redaction boundary",
      "description": "```go\n// Package export is Balaur's sovereign-export mirror (plans 192/194): a one-way,\n// read-only renderer of the active knowledge record to Markdown. ...\n// The redaction boundary is hard: it reads ONLY the `nodes` collection,\n// ONLY status=active rows, and never touches any secret/token\n// collection (api_key, OAuth tokens, vault entries — see the design note at\n// docs/superpowers/specs/2026-06-25-sovereign-export-design.md).\n```\n\nThe package header is a policy statement, not just documentation. The redaction boundary has three independent layers:\n\n- **Collection scope**: only `nodes` is ever queried. `llm_providers`, `llm_models`, `extensions`, `owner_settings`, `audit_log`, `conversations`, `messages` — none of them are imported or called in this package.\n- **Status filter**: `nodes.ListByTypeStatus(app, typ, nodes.StatusActive)` — proposed, rejected, and archived nodes are never read. The filter is in the one shared reader, not scattered across call sites.\n- **Type deferral**: `day` and `task` are in `deferredTypes` and skipped before any read attempt. Their content (task bodies, day recap transcripts) needs its own future redaction pass.\n\nThe consequence: a correctly functioning `ExportMirror` physically cannot leak an API key, OAuth token, or vault entry — it never reads any collection that holds them. The canary test in step 15.6 verifies this at runtime.\n\nNote the package comment says \"no encryption yet — that is Phase 3\" — `encrypt.go` (steps 15.5) landed as that Phase 3."
    },
    {
      "file": "internal/export/encrypt.go",
      "line": 57,
      "title": "15.5 — Passphrase encryption: scrypt + AES-256-GCM",
      "description": "```go\nfunc EncryptDir(srcDir, destFile, passphrase string) error\n```\n\n`EncryptDir` wraps the already-written Markdown mirror tree into a single encrypted archive. The design:\n\n1. **Tar first**: `tarDir(srcDir)` builds a deterministic in-memory tar of the mirror tree (files sorted so the archive byte order is stable).\n2. **Key derivation**: `scrypt.Key(passphrase, salt, N=32768, r=8, p=1)` → 32-byte key. `N=1<<15` is the standard interactive cost: ~100ms on modern hardware, expensive enough to resist offline dictionary attacks.\n3. **AES-256-GCM**: 32-byte key → 256-bit AES → GCM authenticated-encryption mode. GCM provides both confidentiality and integrity; tampering with a single byte fails the auth tag.\n4. **Envelope header**: a small plaintext preamble (`BALAUREX` magic, version byte, warning flag, 16-byte salt, GCM nonce) is also bound as GCM additional-authenticated-data — so tampering with any header byte also fails decryption. `ErrBadPassphrase` is returned for any auth failure, whether wrong passphrase or corrupted bytes.\n5. **No PocketBase reads**: `EncryptDir` takes a directory path, not a `core.App` — it adds no new collection-read surface beyond the mirror `ExportMirror` already wrote.\n\n`ErrBadPassphrase` (line 49) is the sentinel callers test with `errors.Is`. `DecryptDir` holds plaintext fully in memory and untars only after `gcm.Open` succeeds — so a wrong passphrase writes nothing to `destDir`.\n\nAll primitives come from the Go standard library and `golang.org/x/crypto/scrypt` — CGO stays off throughout. The design note: *the secret lives only in the owner's head; no escrow, no cloud, no key-on-disk. A lost passphrase means a lost backup.* That warning is literally encoded in the `envWarning` constant and stored in the archive header.\n\nSee **Tour 00** (step 0.1) for the CGO-free build constraint that governs all of Balaur."
    },
    {
      "file": "internal/export/mirror_test.go",
      "line": 229,
      "title": "15.6 — The canary test",
      "description": "```go\nfunc TestMirrorNeverLeaksStoredSecret(t *testing.T) {\n    ...\n    const secret = \"sk-SECRET-TOKEN-DO-NOT-LEAK\"\n    store.SaveCloudModel(app, \"TestProvider\", \"https://example.test\",\n        secret, \"Test\", \"test-model\", \"\")\n    ...\n    export.ExportMirror(app, dir)\n    for name, content := range readAll(t, dir) {\n        if strings.Contains(content, secret) {\n            t.Fatalf(\"STORED SECRET LEAKED into %s ...\", name, content)\n        }\n    }\n}\n```\n\nThis is the **extended canary test** — the regression that makes the redaction boundary machine-checkable rather than review-only.\n\nWhat it does:\n1. Creates a real PocketBase app with `storetest.NewApp(t)` (a temp-dir instance, no mock).\n2. Writes a real API key into `llm_providers.api_key` via `store.SaveCloudModel` — the same path the owner uses when adding a cloud model from the Models page.\n3. Creates a few ordinary active nodes (note, person) that contain no secrets.\n4. Calls `ExportMirror` over the full app.\n5. Reads every file in the output directory and asserts the secret string does not appear in any of them.\n\nA failure means `ExportMirror` read a collection it should not have. The test comment says: **this canary must never be deleted or weakened.** It is the enforcement mechanism for the redaction policy stated in the package header (step 15.4).\n\nNote the test uses `readAll` to scan recursively — it checks the full JD tree, not just the root — so a future folder reorganization cannot hide a leak.\n\nSee **Tour 04** for the testing patterns (fake clients, `t.TempDir`, table-driven tests) used throughout Balaur."
    }
  ]
}
